column58: Healthcare Services National Guidance  General Guidance  •	Masking is required indoors and in case of a gathering of over 50 people outdoors  •	Workers and visitors who are neither recovered nor vaccinated are required to wear a mask next to patients also in outdoor areas  •	Violation of the guidance shall incur a fine    Health and Social Services Facilities  •	Health and social services facilities are geriatric hospitals, homes for the frail operated by social services, assisted living facilities operated by social services, housing for people with disabilities operated by the social services, housing complexes operated by the Ministry of Housing and Integration, mental health hostels, community housing for the rehabilitation of people with mental health disabilities and facilities for rehabilitation from drug and alcohol abuse that include housing  •	Visitors (aged 3 and older) who are vaccinated or recovered will present a certificate attesting to a negative result on an antigen test administered by an official facility, or a signed declaration that they tested positive on a home antigen test kit, administered in the 24 hours preceding the visit.  •	Visitors (aged 3 and older) who are unvaccinated or non-infected will present a certificate attesting to a negative result on an antigen test administered by an official facility.  •	The number of visitors per tenant or permanent resident – no more than 1 visitor per day, not including minor visitors who are accompanied by an adult.    Activities Subject to the Green Pass Scheme  •	Visitors eligible to be admitted to places operating subject to the Green Pass Scheme:  •	Vaccinated individuals, according to the Ministry of Health's definition  •	Recovered individuals, according to the Ministry of Health's definition  •	Those who tested negative in a paid PCR test valid for 72 hours from the time of sampling  •	Children under 12 and 3 months who tested negative in a PCR test taken as part of Magen Education program, effective for up to one week from the date of sampling  •	Those who tested negative in a rapid test taken up to 24 hours before arrival in the venue    Exempt from the Green Pass Scheme:  •	Children under 3  •	Children under 12 and 3 months who present a certificate of disability from the National Insurance Institute of Israel    Sources:  https://archive.vn/uddYq [Local Councils Traffic Light Model - Red Locality]  https://archive.vn/eHMBE [Local Councils Traffic Light Model - Red Locality - text only]

column9: no changes in policy, green passes are still required for university students.    Starting September 1st green passes are required for School Personnel only. Starting Dec 6th a vaccine mandate is in place for all school personnel.   University students still need to hold a green pass to attend lessons in presence.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211210170128/https://www.wired.it/article/green-pass-scuola-universita-regole-vaccino-mezzi/

column45: Although the methodology to perform contact tracing has not changed (all close contacts need to be tested or self-quarantine if they don't want to be tested), since the end of December contact tracing has been struggling to trace all close contacts of positives. column9: Despite increasing cases, schools continue to remain open.  Schools are to continue undergoing stringent sanitation and infection prevention measures, increased ventilation measures, and distribute rapid antigen test kits. Students with illness symptoms are not to attend schools. Individual schools may also have the jurisdiction to close due to in-school outbreaks on a school-by-school basis.  Schools have also resumed all club activities, events, and excursions; however strict infection control measures must be followed.    https://archive.fo/yw3cF (Japan emergency measures)  https://web.archive.org/web/20211008192307/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20211005/k10013291931000.html (school measures)  https://web.archive.org/web/20211130012156/https://www.bousai.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/1009757/1020631.html (Tokyo basic measures from Dec 1)  https://web.archive.org/web/20211130012221/https://www.bousai.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/1009757/1020626.html (Tokyo basic gathering measures from Dec 1)  https://web.archive.org/web/20211130012732/https://www.pref.okinawa.lg.jp/site/chijiko/koho/corona/documents/1125hoshin_1.pdf (Okinawa basic measures from Nov 25)  https://archive.fo/PdDnL

column24: The government continues to encourage people to avoid dense crowds and situations of high risk for infection, to refrain for unnecessary movement to areas with high infection rates.    https://archive.fo/yw3cF (Japan emergency measures)
column27: The government continues to encourage residents to practice precautions moving between prefectures, particularly to and from areas of high infection rates and particularly for those unvaccinated.    https://archive.fo/yw3cF (Japan emergency measures)
column32: No change to previous policy. New unemployment subsidy application deadlines for January-March 2022 have been set for June 30, 2022 (support document revised as of Dec 23rd).  The Japan Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare continues to provide financial support in the forms of: employment subsidies to encourage business owners to maintain employees, leave of absence due to COVID-19 infection, living expenses for leave of absence or the unemployed, and special support for low-income child-rearing households for a maximum of 50,000 yen per child. Employment subsidies have a maximum of 15,000 yen per day per person.    https://archive.fo/HTePO
column34: No change to previous policy. New debt relief subsidy application deadlines for January-March 2022 have been set for June 30, 2022 (support document revised as of Dec 23rd).  The Japan Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare continues to provide debt relief: loans for small-lot emergency funds and comprehensive unemployment funds are provided at interest-free and payments may be deferred up to one year. Housing security loans are available for those at risk of losing housing: rent payments may be deferred up to 9-months with evidence of employment search. Property tax exemption may be available for applicants facing declining income or unemployment due to the pandemic. For single-parent households, family housing support loan of upto 40,000 yen for 12 months is available interest-free for a one-time redemption if the parent continues to work for a year. Interviews for single-parent households will be conducted to understand their living conditions, motivation for employment, efforts to acquire qualifications, etc. A policy is also in place for the deferment for payments of national taxes.    https://archive.fo/HTePO
column41: Comprehensive public information about COVID-19 continues to be disseminated by the government.    https://archive.fo/Qm0IZ  https://archive.fo/6jEXK
column45: In Tokyo, of the 25 people tested positive for the omicron strain, 11 had no history of travel and were community-acquired infections. Tokyo is expecting rapid increase in omicron cases as a result of the year-end holidays.    https://archive.fo/OldDN
column52: No change to previous policy. The wearing of facial masks in Japan is wide spread and continues to be recommended by the government. Masks should also be worn in schools by students and faculty members, and should only be removed when eating or partaking in physical activities.    https://archive.fo/yw3cF (Japan emergency measures)
column58: No change to previous policy. The government now allows visitations at long-term care homes restricted to visitors who have been fully vaccinated with two doses of the COVID-19 vaccination or have had a negative PCR test prior to the visitation.    Last report on provisional measures in nursing homes was published as of December 27, 2021.  The following preventative measures for the elderly also continue to be conducted:  - Recommendations and communications for active/healthy living and staying indoors targeted towards senior citizens.  - Monthly evaluation of preventive and infection control measures within long-term care homes.  - Supply infection prevention items such as masks, other PPE, and disinfectants,  - Comprehensive information and training material for Long Term Care staff and ownership including donning/doffing of PPE, systematic area zoning within facilities, and procedures involving admissions, discharge, hygiene and garbage.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211130023257/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20211125/k10013360411000.html  https://archive.fo/d3uUA  https://web.archive.org/web/20211213153423/https://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/seisakunitsuite/bunya/hukushi_kaigo/kaigo_koureisha/taisakumatome_13635.html

column9: On January 7, Okinawa Prefecture begins to distribute school attendance to reduce the spread of infection. Schools will be divided into groups and attend in-person on certain days of the week while attending remote learning on alternate days.    As a result of high case counts, the prefectures, Okinawa, Hiroshima, and Yamaguchi will implement priority countermeasures beginning January 9, 2022 (until 31st).    https://web.archive.org/web/20220108012250/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20220107/k10013418911000.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220108010037/https://corona.go.jp/emergency/
column12: As a result of high case counts, the prefectures, Okinawa, Hiroshima, and Yamaguchi will implement priority countermeasures beginning January 9, 2022 (until 31st). These measures include closing restaurants and retail from 8/9PM and to refrain from serving alcohol. Upper limit for event gatherings will also be limited to a maximum of 5,000 or half of the venue's capacity, whichever is the smallest number of attendees.  From January 11, 2022 in Tokyo (until 31st), restaurants certified by the local government may continue to serve patrons up to a limit of 8 people per table. Vaccination certificate app should be used on groups with more than 5 people. For stores not certified by the city, they will limit customers to 4 people per group and close by 9PM.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220108010037/https://corona.go.jp/emergency/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220108012419/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20220107/k10013420601000.html (gatherings in Okinawa, Hiroshima, Yamaguchi)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220108012611/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20220105/k10013416701000.html (stores in Okinawa, Hiroshima, Yamaguchi)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220108012952/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20220107/k10013419911000.html (stores in Tokyo)

column9: Myanmar reopened all basic education schools on Monday, including private schools and Buddhist monastic schools, with a decrease in daily Covid-19 infections in the country.    According to an announcement of Central Committee on Prevention, Control and Treatment for Covid-19, schools in 46 townships of nine regions and states will be excluded from reopening based on the analysis on the test positivity rates per 100,000 people in the past 14 days.    Since the COVID-19 infection has been under control in Myanmar, the universities, degree colleges and colleges under the Higher Education Department of the Ministry of Education opened on Thursday.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111055355/https:/www.myanmaritv.com/news/university-education-fourth-year-and-post-graduate-courses-opened  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111060346/https:/www.thestar.com.my/aseanplus/aseanplus-news/2021/11/01/myanmar-reopens-schools-amid-drop-in-new-covid-19-cases

column29: Commercial flights are operating but with limited availability. The Civil Aviation Authority of Nepal (CAAN) has announced that all domestic flights have resumed, and strict COVID protocols are enforced. Operation of cargo flights, rescue flights, and evacuation flights will be carried out subject to special permission.  Please US embassy link last updated 04/10/21  https://web.archive.org/web/20211115064301/https://np.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/     Effective September 24, all fully vaccinated foreigners arriving in Nepal via the immigration office at the airport or a land border can receive on-arrival visas. No quarantine required. Fully-vaccinated travellers travelling to Nepal must present the following documents:  1.Evidence of completion of a 14 day post-COVID-19 vaccination incubation period  2.COVID-19 negative PCR test report obtained within 72 hours of entry into Nepal    On-arrival visas at land border entries are not available to unvaccinated travelers. All unvaccinated and semi-vaccinated travelers must comply with the Government of Nepal’s 10-day quarantine mandate, which requires quarantine at a local hotel at their own cost. A PCR test must be completed and returned negative on 11th day before travelling within the country will be permitted. Such travelers must present the following documents:  1.COVID-19 negative PCR test report obtained within 72 hours of entering the country

column29: As of January,05,2022, the Pakistani government has modified its international travel rules. Categorical classification of countries is no longer valid, effectively lifting travel bans from category C locations, including several African and European countries, and Hong Kong among others. Revised rules mandate inbound passengers to hold proof of completing vaccination if above 18 years old and negative results of a PCR test obtained within 48 hours before departure if older than six years. They must continue to submit a health declaration from online or via the Pass Track mobile application within 48 hours before arrival. Returning Pakistani citizens unable to avail of vaccination due to visa or medical issues, as well as Afghan citizens entering via land borders, are exempt from carrying vaccination certificate. Passengers arriving via direct flights from Europe will undergo an on arrival rapid antigen test (RAT); officials will also administer RAT to 50% of arrivals from Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, as well as a random selection of passengers from other countries. Passengers with positive RAT test results must quarantine for 10 days at a government or self-paid facility, those who test positive on the mandatory PCR test on the eighth day must undergo additional quarantine until they return negative result in a PCR test. Source: Garda World  Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220109175054/https://www.garda.com/crisis24/news-alerts/562991/pakistan-authorities-lift-travel-bans-modify-entry-testing-restrictions-as-of-jan-5-update-64

column29: Peruvians, resident foreigners, and non-resident foreigners, aged 12 years and over, whose final travel destination is Peru, must prove that they have completed, in Peru and/or abroad, their vaccination scheme against COVID-19, fourteen (14) days before boarding at your point of origin; otherwise, they can present a negative molecular test, with a result date of no more than 72 hours before boarding at their point of origin. Children under twelve only need to be asymptomatic to board.    Peruvian passengers and resident foreigners from the Republic of South Africa and the Republic of Botswana, or who have made a stopover in these places, must prove that they have completed, in Peru and/or abroad, their vaccination scheme against COVID- 19, and have a negative molecular test, with a result date of no more than 48 hours before boarding at your point of origin. column9: SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Puerto Rico’s governor announced Wednesday that he will delay the start of classes at public schools by two weeks and recommended private schools do the same. The public school year is scheduled to resume Jan. 24, with Gov. Pedro Pierluisi stressing that all those working in the education sector are required to have their booster shot by Jan. 15. In addition, schoolchildren age 5 and older are required to have at least their first dose by Jan. 10.  https://archive.fo/LJvGh

column9: No Coding Changes to the period of 01-06 January 2022. Recent updates from the government states that in light of the Omicron variant, the current Covid-19 safety measurements will remain unchanged right into the Chinese New Year (CNY) period - this commences on the 01-02 February 2022 and normally the period stretches for 14 days.  ________________________    Quote (1):  "SINGAPORE - Singapore's current set of Covid-19 safe management rules will stay in place during the upcoming Chinese New Year period from Feb 1, in view of a likely surge of infections brought about by the new Omicron variant, said Finance Minister Lawrence Wong on Wednesday (Jan 5). Group sizes for gathering and dining at restaurants have been capped at five since November, when Singapore emerged from an outbreak caused by the earlier Delta variant. Mr Wong, who is a co-chair of the multi-ministry task force handling Covid-19, said during a press conference that the present posture would be maintained as he could not imagine the Omicron wave passing before Chinese New Year."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20220106084209/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/current-covid-19-rules-will-stay-during-cny-period-in-view-of-omicron-wave-lawrence-wong.    ______________________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 18 Dec 2021:    No Coding changes to the period of 14-18 Dec.  School holidays remain and school resumes in early January 2022. _______________     ***Please refer to notes dated 19 Nov 2021:  No further changes to schools opening [Link (1,2)]. Year-end School holidays to begin this Sat 20 Nov 2021, schools will reopen in 2022 [Link(3)]. Current evidence suggests that transmission of COVID-19 occurs primarily through the respiratory droplets of infected people, which are expelled when an infected person coughs, sneezes, talks or sings. These respiratory droplets can reach the eyes, nose or mouth of a susceptible person directly or indirectly (via contaminated surfaces), resulting in infection.    Airborne transmission of the virus can occur in health care settings where aerosol-generating procedures are performed. While there have been limited reports of airborne transmission outside of health care settings internationally, its role and extent are under further study. MOH will continue to monitor the evidence as it emerges.    To reduce the risk of spread, members of public must wear a mask outside the home and observe safe distancing. Individuals should also observe good hand hygiene and avoid crowded spaces if possible."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211119095432/https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19/general

Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211213094222/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/100-worth-of-cdc-vouchers-for-each-sporean-household-available-for-collection-online  ________________    Quote (2): [Exchange Rate]  "Dec 13, 2021 09:38 UTC  Singapore Dollar	130,000,000.00 SGD	  US Dollar	95035922.924214	@ 1.367904"    Link (2): https://web.archive.org/web/20211213094242/https://www.x-rates.com/historical/?from=SGD&amount=130000000&date=2021-12-13  ______________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 19 Nov 2021:    No coding changes for the period of 07-19 Nov 2021.     ____________________________________  ****Please refer to previous notes dated 6 Nov 2021:    no coding changes to the period of 02-06 Nov 2021.   ___________________  ***Please refer to notes dates 01 Nov 2021:    No coding changes for the period of 24 Oct -01 Nov.  ___________________  *** Please refer to notes dates 23 Oct 2021    Support to continue until Nov 21 in light of the further extensions of the current restrictions.  ___________________    Quote (1):  "SINGAPORE: A S$640 million support package will be rolled out for affected businesses and workers, after it was announced on Wednesday (Oct 20) that Singapore will extend its COVID-19 restrictions by nearly a month.  The stabilisation phase, which started on Sep 27 to help reduce the strain on the healthcare system, was scheduled to last until Oct 24.   It has now been extended until Nov 21, with a review of the measures at the two-week mark. They may be adjusted based on the situation then, said the Ministry of Health (MOH) in a media release.  During the stabilisation phase, social gatherings and dining-in have been capped at groups of two, while work-from-home has been the default arrangement.  Given the extended restrictions, the Government will continue with the Jobs Support Scheme until Nov 21, at 25 per cent wage support for sectors significantly affected by the tightened measures.  These include F&B, retail, cinemas, museums and art galleries, family entertainment, tourism, gyms and fitness studios, as well as performing arts and arts education.  A two-week rental waiver will be given to qualifying tenants on government-owned commercial properties.  Eligible tenant-occupiers and owner-occupiers of privately-owned commercial properties will also be given a 0.5-month rental relief cash payout under the Rental Support Scheme (RSS).  Cooked food and market stallholders in centres managed by the National Environment Agency (NEA) or operators appointed by NEA will receive a 0.5-month rental waiver.    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211023041636/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/singapore/covid-19-support-package-jobs-support-scheme-extended-restrictions-2257036

Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211023041636/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/singapore/covid-19-support-package-jobs-support-scheme-extended-restrictions-2257036  ____________________________________  ***Please refer to notes dates 18 Oct 2021:    No coding changes for the period of 09-18 Oct 2021.  ___________________________  **** Please refer to notes dated 08 Oct 2021:    no coding changes for the period of 06-08 Oct 2021.  _______________________________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 05 Oct 2021:    No coding changes to the period of 26 Sep to 05 Oct 2021.  ____________________    ***Please refer to notes dated 25 Sep 2021:  No coding changes to the period of 20-25 Sep 2021.   ____________  Quote (1):  "COVID-19 Recovery Grant - Temporary  The COVID-19 Recovery Grant – Temporary (CRG-T) provides temporary financial support for lower- and middle-income workers who have been placed on involuntary no-pay leave (NPL), or face income loss of at least 50% for one month, as a result of the tightened safe management measures (SMMs) during this period of Heightened Alert."    "COVID-19 Recovery Grant  The COVID-19 Recovery Grant (CRG) will help those with:    Loss of job (i.e. retrenchment, termination of employment contract)  Eligible to receive support of up to $700/month for 3 months   Involuntary No-Pay Leave (NPL) for at least 3 consecutive months  Loss of at least 50% salary on average for at least 3 consecutive months  Eligible to receive support of up to $500/month for 3 months  Loss of at least 50% Net Trade Income (NTI) on average for Self-Employed Persons (SEPs) for at least 3 consecutive months'    "The Courage Fund For Lower-Income Households affected by COVID-19  Target beneficiaries and eligibility criteria  The Courage Fund will help lower-income households affected by COVID-19 who meet the following criteria:  At least one household member is a Singapore Citizen or Permanent Resident.  At least one household member contracted COVID-19, or was placed on Stay-Home Notice (SHN), mandatory Leave of Absence (LOA) or Home Quarantine Order (QO).  [As of 1 Aug 2021] Household has current gross monthly income of =$6,200, or current gross monthly per capita income of =$2,000.  Household experienced a complete or partial (of at least 10%) loss of household income as a result of (2).  Households who have been affected by QO/SHN/LOA or from contracting COVID-19 more than once and continue to face protracted job or income loss can apply and receive up to two tranches of support, if they meet the other eligibility criteria.    Note: ComCare clients can apply.    Assistance provided  For each tranche, a one-time lump sum of up to $1,000 (depending on the household's per capita income after being affected by COVID-19), credited into bank account.  Please allow 2 - 3 weeks processing time for fund disbursement, upon submission of supporting documents."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20210925062514/https://www.msf.gov.sg/assistance/Pages/covid19relief.aspx  ________________________  Point (2):  Various schemes are available with the government setting up an online site to help individuals navigate the right places to get support.    Link (2): http://web.archive.org/web/20210925062832/https://supportgowhere.life.gov.sg/  _______________________    Quote (3):  "Suspension of Repayment and Interest Accrual of Government loans:   Suspension of repayment and interest accrual of Tuition Fee Loan (TFL), Study Loan (SL), and Overseas Student Programme Loan (OSPL) for all Autonomous University and polytechnic graduates  ? There is no need to apply. All individuals with outstanding TFL, SL and OSPL will be automatically granted the suspension until 30 September 2021. "    "Loan Support:  - Temporary Bridging Loan Programme: Enhanced support for enterprises’ working capital needs, to ease enterprises’ access to credit and ready them for the new normal   - Enterprise Financing Scheme (Trade Loan):  Enhanced support for enterprises’ trade financing needs, to ease enterprises’ access to credit and ready them for the new normal  - Enterprise Financing Scheme – Venture Debt: Finance the growth of innovative enterprises using Venture Debt and Warrants"    Link (3): http://archive.today/2021.09.25-063116/https://www.mof.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider3/budget2021/download/pdf/fy2021_budget_navigator.pdf    ___________________________________________________________  ***Please refer to notes dated 10 Sep 2021:    No coding changes to the period of 07-10 Sep 2021.  __________________________  ***Please refer to notes dated 06 Sep 2021:    Please refer to notes dated 14th June 2021:  No coding changes to the period of 06-14 June 2021.  ________________________________________  Quote (1):  "S$1.3 billion worth of GST voucher payments will be disbursed from June, benefiting about 1.4 million Singaporeans and 950,000 households, the Ministry of Finance (MOF) said on Tuesday (Jun 1). The vouchers combine regular payments as well as one-off payments that are part of the S$900 million Household Support Package introduced to help families during this period of uncertainty amid COVID-19. Lower- to middle-income families are set to receive more support from the package, which was announced at Budget 2021 in February.FOR     INDIVIDUAL CITIZENS  About 1.4 million citizens will receive up to S$500 in GST vouchers this year. This comprises a one-off GST Voucher - Cash Special Payment of S$200 and a regular GST Voucher - Cash payment of up to S$300. The one-off payment and regular payment will be credited directly to citizens' bank accounts from Jun 23 and Jul 30 respectively, if they have linked their NRIC to their PayNow accounts.    FOR HOUSEHOLDS    About 950,000 Singaporean households living in public housing will receive their quarterly GST Voucher - U-Save rebates in July.  The households will also receive an additional 50 per cent rebate through a one-off GST Voucher - U-Save Special Payment.  In total, a household can expect to receive between S$355 and S$595 in rebates in financial year 2021, depending on the flat type.    Other government payments that eligible citizens can expect to receive later this year include the Five-Year MediSave Top-up scheme, grocery vouchers and top-ups to children's education accounts, said MOF. Households can also expect to receive rebates on service and conservancy charges and Community Development Council vouchers.     Link (1):  http://web.archive.org/web/20210614134834/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/gst-voucher-u-save-cash-special-payment-mof-14924902      __________________  *** Please refer to notes dated 31 May 2021:  No coding changes for the period of 22-31 May 2021. However, new announcements have been made on the 28th of May to roll out further financial assisstance in light of the recent tightening of covid measures which saw many businesses like restaurants see an economic dive as footfall dwindles and diners barred from eating in. This in turn affected the wages of employees and their ability to make regular payments  such as monthly bills.  ___________________    Quote (1):  "3. Rental relief  Rental relief will be given to small and medium-sized enterprises and non-profit organisations with an annual revenue of not more than $100 million which are tenant-occupiers of some commercial properties. The Government will grant one month of rental relief for qualifying tenants in government-owned commercial properties. A similar one-month rental waiver had been announced earlier for hawker stalls and coffee shops. For privately owned commercial properties, the Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore (Iras) will disburse a half-month rental relief cash payout to qualifying tenants as part of a new scheme, called the Rental Support Scheme."    "4. Suspension of repayment for tuition fee loans  The Ministry of Education (MOE) will extend the suspension of loan repayment and interest charges for another four months until Sept 30. This applies to tuition fee loans, study loans and overseas student programme loans for all autonomous university and polytechnic graduates. MOE had earlier suspended these charges for one year, from June 1 last year to May 31."    Link (1):  http://archive.today/2021.05.31-155012/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/stepped-up-jobs-support-scheme-subsidies-temporary-relief-grant-for-workers-affected-by  _________________________    Quote (2):  "Rental relief will also be given to small and medium-sized enterprises as well as eligible non-profit organisations in commercial properties, while eligible lower- to middle-income workers and self-employed workers whose income have been affected by the measures can receive a one-off payout of up to $700 under a new Covid-19 Recovery Grant (Temporary)."    "Some support has been given to businesses and workers to cushion the impact of the measures, but companies have sought more help from landlords and the Government. For instance, food and beverage businesses will get 50 per cent wage subsidies under the JSS during the period for which dining in is prohibited, up from 10 per cent. Hawkers and coffee shop stallholders who are tenants of government agencies will also get a one-month rental waiver." Mr Wong, who is a co-chair of the multi-ministry task force handling Covid-19, said during a press conference that the present posture would be maintained as he could not imagine the Omicron wave passing before Chinese New Year."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20220106084209/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/current-covid-19-rules-will-stay-during-cny-period-in-view-of-omicron-wave-lawrence-wong.    ______________________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 18 Dec 2021:    "No coding changes for the period of 14-18 Dec 2021.   ___________   ***Please refer to notes dated 13 Dec 2021:  No coding changes to the period of 03-13 Dec 2021.   ______________________________________   *** Please refer to notes dated 02 Dec 2021:    No coding changes to the period of 22Nov - 02 Dec 2021. Resumption of in-person visits have commenced, however, each institution have implemented tight restrictions with regards to how in-person visits will take place. An example of a Nursing in Singapore is below.    _____________   Quote (1):   "RESUMPTION of face-to-face visits in OVNH, for both FULLY VACCINATED (“FV”) residents and visitors. Only 1 designated fully vaccinated visitor allowed per visit per day for each fully vaccinated resident, for a maximum of 30 mins each time.  Visitation hours are from 10am - 2pm and 4pm - 8pm daily.  Video calls and telephone calls remain for Unvaccinated residents. Please call our branches to pre-register. Thank you for your support as we do our utmost best during this period.  • Balestier: (65) 6250 6636 • Changi : (65) 6545 5977 • Clementi: (65) 6873 9988 • Marsiling : (65) 6362 7333 • Simei: (65) 6260 0020  Please note: ? Each FV resident will be allowed 3 designated FV visitors, maximum of 1 visitation per week. ? Only 1 designated FV visitor per FV resident will be allowed per visit per day for a maximum of 30 mins each time. ? The same designated FV visitor must have an interval of 10 days before their next visitation. ? Non-designated FV visitors will not be allowed to enter the premises. ? No outside food is allowed."    Link (1): http://archive.today/2021.12.02-033425/https://www.facebook.com/OVNHSG/

column29: Timor-Leste Travel update from UK government website:  -A State of Emergency is no longer in place in Timor-Leste. The latest one ended on 28 November 2021. Entry to national territory is no longer subject to authorisation from the Prime Minister, while entry to the country continues to be subject to medical screening. If a passenger is found infected with COVID-19, he or she will be taken to quarantine for further consultation and treatment. All passengers travelling to Timor-Leste should always present to the airport competent authorities the following: vaccination certificate and a negative COVID-19 PCR test result done within the last 72 hours before the time of departure. The test needs to be in one of these language: Indonesian, Portuguese or English. Failure to present the two documents, will be subjected to 14 days of quarantine.  -It is mandatory for all individuals to practice COVID-19 safety measures, including wearing a mask, washing hands frequently, and maintaining social distance of at least two metres.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221559/https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/timor-leste/coronavirus

column9: Several school districts across the country are remaining closed to in-person learning following the holiday break.     See Pennsylvania:   Latest bulletin:   As we begin the new year, school leaders are requesting updated COVID-19 guidance, particularly to changes that have occurred to the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) close contact and quarantine practices.    At this time, schools should follow the most recent PA Department of Health (DOH) Health Alert (PA-HAN) on Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population that was released last Thursday. (615 - 12/30/2021 - UPD - UPDATE: Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population (PDF))    As with previous updates in guidance, schools are expected to follow the new community guidelines. The CDC has indicated that there will be additional guidance for more specific settings, including schools, released in the near future. DOH will review and update the community guidance in the PA-HAN accordingly if and when CDC makes any further adjustments. Please note that this is a very fluid situation. We appreciate your patience as we work through these changes together.    https://archive.vn/pEyJ8    Two southeastern Pennsylvania school districts announces school closures due to the coronavirus on the heels of their winter breaks.  The Upper Darby and Lower Merion school districts closed schools Monday as case counts rise.  In Lower Merion: If district schools have adequate staffing, in-person learning will resume Tuesday.  Students will also have the option to learn virtually through Jan. 14.  https://archive.vn/UWo4W
column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States." column43: Testing is generally available across the US.     See North Carolina:   Fully vaccinated individuals should get tested if they:  -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.  -Have had close contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. You should get tested within 3-5 days after exposure.  -Are traveling internationally and returning to the United States. Fully vaccinated international travelers are required to get tested three days before travel by air into the U.S. and should also get tested 3-5 days after their trip.    Unvaccinated individuals should get tested if they:   -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.   -Have come in contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. If they do not have symptoms, they should wait at least six days after their last known exposure to COVID-19 before they get tested.  -Take part in activities that put them at higher risk for COVID-19 because they cannot physically distance as needed to avoid exposure, such as travel, attending large social or mass gatherings, or being in crowded or poorly ventilated indoor settings.    If available through an employer or another organization, unvaccinated individuals can be part of a program where they get tested regularly for COVID-19.    See Archive:  https://archive.vn/fUjTw

column43: Testing is open and available to all – no eligibility requirements or symptomatic requirements. There are no out-of-pocket costs for COVID-19 testing at a testing site. An insured person can get a COVID-19 test when needed by any provider, in or out of their health plan network, at no cost. If you’re uninsured, the government pays for your test. column45: Contact tracing is primarily conducted at the state level, but the CDC is serving in both a guiding and supportive role with contact tracing. column52: Everyone is required to wear masks in:  Indoor public spaces (until February 15, 2022)  Workplaces (until February 15, 2022)  Public transit  Healthcare settings (including long term care facilities)  Adult and senior care facilities  Indoors in K-12 schools, childcare, and other youth settings  State and local correctional facilities and detention centers  Homeless shelters, emergency shelters, and cooling centers  Masks are required for unvaccinated people and recommended for everyone in:  Places of worship    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221451/https://covid19.ca.gov/masks-and-ppe/
column55: Any Californian aged 5 and up can get vaccinated, for free.     See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221624/https://covid19.ca.gov/vaccines/
column58: "Visitors who are unvaccinated or incompletely vaccinated must show documentation of a negative SARS-CoV-2 test that occurred within 72 hours before each indoor visit."   "Any visitor entering the facility, regardless of their vaccination status, must adhere to the following:    "All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must be screened for fever and COVID-19 symptoms and/or exposure within the prior 14 days to another person with COVID-19; if a visitor has COVID-19 symptoms or has been in close contact with a confirmed positive case, they must reschedule their visit, regardless of their vaccination status.  All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must wear a well-fitting face mask (medical masks, also called surgical masks, or double masking is recommended) and perform hand hygiene upon entry and in all common areas in the facility;   If personal protective equipment (PPE) is required for contact with the resident due to quarantine or COVID-19 positive isolation status (including fully vaccinated visitors), it must be donned and doffed according to instruction by HCP.  All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must follow physical distancing guidelines and maintain at least 6 feet distance from other visitors from different households, as well as from facility staff and other residents;   Facilities should limit visitor movement in the facility, regardless of the visitor's vaccination status; for example, visitors should not walk around the hallways of the facility and should go directly to and from the resident's room or designated visitation area."    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221827/https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHCQ/LCP/Pages/AFL-20-22.aspx

column9: According to January 2 report,  "Multiple school districts across Connecticut have canceled classes for Monday because of an increase in COVID-19 cases statewide.All after school activities and Enfield Adult Education Classes are also canceled.There is no out-of-town buses."    Coded 1G since closing of schools is increasing due to increased covid 19 cases. Ansonia schools are closed for the week.    So many school employees in Ansonia are affected by the virus, the school system can no longer safely provide in-person instruction, Joseph DiBacco, superintendent of schools, said in a letter to parents. Remote learning is no longer an option, he said."  Coded 1G since school closing recommendation is taking place across all US states.    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.courant.com/coronavirus/hc-news-coronavirus-school-closures-delays-20220103-zgx54x7fwrdqflaazpabpbyuqm-story.html
column12: According to a published report by CDC workplaces are obliged to:  "Develop an Infectious Disease Preparedness  and Response Plan  If one does not already exist, develop an infectious disease  preparedness and response plan that can help guide protective  actions against COVID-19.  Stay abreast of guidance from federal, state, local, tribal, and/or  territorial health agencies, and consider how to incorporate those  recommendations and resources into workplace-specific plans.  Plans should consider and address the level(s) of risk  associated with various worksites and job tasks workers  perform at those sites. Such considerations may include:  ■ Where, how, and to what sources of SARS-CoV-2 might  workers be exposed, including:  { The general public, customers, and coworkers; and  { Sick individuals or those at particularly high risk  of infection (e.g., international travelers who have  visited locations with widespread sustained (ongoing)  COVID-19 transmission, healthcare workers who have  had unprotected exposures to people known to have, or  suspected of having, COVID-19).  ■ Non-occupational risk factors at home and in community  settings.    Coded 0 since work places are not closing down.    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.osha.gov/sites/default/files/publications/OSHA3990.pdf

column27: Fully vaccinated visitors (or visitors who tested positive for COVID-19 in the previous 90 days) may travel to DC from domestic locations without quarantining unless showing symptoms of COVID-19. Fully vaccinated is defined as 14 days after the second dose of a 2-dose series, or after one dose of a single-dose vaccine.     Unvaccinated visitors don't need a COVID-19 test if travelling from Maryland and Virginia or if they are in DC less than 24 hours. For non-essential travel, people must get a COVID-19 test 1-3 days before visiting DC. If a traveler tests positive while in DC, they must complete their isolation before traveling home, and susceptible close contacts must complete a 10-day quarantine.  Moreover, a test is required if essential travelers have more than 1 week of notice.     See Archive:  https://archive.vn/KOFps

column9: On Jan. 3, Gov. DeSantis said there would be no school closures despite the surge in Covid-19 cases. However, five school districts “Alachua, Broward, Duval, and Miami-Dade”are issuing face mask mandates to the fullest legal capability, requiring employees, visitors, and vendors to wear masks at schools, including on school buses. “Leon County’s school district is evaluating the need for stepped-up protocols with local health officials and school principals, according to its Twitter channel.” Due to these localized changes, coding will change to a 1T.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220110162937/https://floridaphoenix.com/2022/01/03/desantis-our-schools-will-be-open-despite-surge-in-covid-infections/  https://archive.fo/fhM5i
column52: On Jan. 3, five school districts put in place mask mandates to their maximum legal capabilities, which includes requiring employees, visitors, and vendors to wear masks at schools, including on school buses. A few private schools also have mask mandates in place for students and staff. Thus, coding will change to a 2T.    https://archive.fo/fhM5i

column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals.    The July 29th order from Biden still stands, ordering federal workers to be vaccinated or subject themselves to constant masking and frequent testing.     Given that the public transit policy affects more people and is stricter, this is now coded as a 2G - Universal. column34: The Kansas Emergency Rental Assistance (KERA) program provides rent, utility, and internet assistance to households experiencing financial hardship as a result of the COVID pandemic. Landlords and tenants apply via a joint online process. If the application is approved, the landlord or service provider receives funds directly from KERA and applies KERA funds to the applicant’s account. Approved applicants are eligible for up to 12 months of assistance.    For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/xsXYB

column9: Masking in schools is still required statewide, though schools may opt-out if they have the requisite isolation and quarantine policies.  Additional social distancing restrictions are in place in New Orleans schools, which will require vaccination from February.  New Orleans University (a private university) has delayed it's post-Christmas return by a week.  LDH: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105202915/https://ldh.la.gov/page/4232  WWL_TV on New Orleans schools policy: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105203110/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/new-covid-guidelines-for-new-orleans-schools/ar-AASsgMs  AP on New Orleans University: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105203215/https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/louisiana/articles/2021-12-24/new-orleans-university-delays-return-amid-new-covid-19-wave
column12: In New Orleans, all businesses must, from February 3rd 2022, comply with a variety of safety measures to be allowed to open. These include 6ft social distancing for the unvaccinated, masking in vehicles, regular cleaning, provision for handwashing, installation of 'sneeze-guards', and quarantine for infected employees.  Louisiana Department of Health recommends working from home.  New Orleans Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105203905/https://ready.nola.gov/NOLAReady/media/Documents/Coronavirus/NOHD-Guidelines-for-reopening-Jan-3-Final-CDC_3.pdf // https://web.archive.org/web/20220105204040/https://ready.nola.gov/incident/coronavirus/safe-reopening/  Governor's Press Release: https://web.archive.org/web/20211231162806/https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/3519
column15: Vaccination (1 dose or more) or a negative antigen or PCR test is required to acess public events in New Orleans. In addition, venues must obtain a Special Event permit or a Certificate of Registration to allow live entertainment, and provide a variety of mitigations, including 'A minimum of 10 feet of separation should be provided between the performers and attendees'  New Orleans Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105203905/https://ready.nola.gov/NOLAReady/media/Documents/Coronavirus/NOHD-Guidelines-for-reopening-Jan-3-Final-CDC_3.pdf // https://web.archive.org/web/20220105204040/https://ready.nola.gov/incident/coronavirus/safe-reopening/
column18: In New Orleans, proof of vaccination or a negative antigen or PCR test is required to attend all indoor gatherings and outdoor gatherings of more than 500 people. Masks are strongly encouraged.  Statewide, on December 30th 2021 Governor Edwards urged Louisanans to celebrate the New Year with their families at home.  New Orleans Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20220105203905/https://ready.nola.gov/NOLAReady/media/Documents/Coronavirus/NOHD-Guidelines-for-reopening-Jan-3-Final-CDC_3.pdf // https://web.archive.org/web/20220105204040/https://ready.nola.gov/incident/coronavirus/safe-reopening/  Governor's Press Release: https://web.archive.org/web/20211231162806/https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/3519

column45: Massachusetts's Community Tracing Collaborative program ended in December 2021. The program was created "to help support local health departments from every community in their contact tracing work. The program focuses on reaching out to people who have tested positive for COVID-19 and the contacts they have been close to, making sure they have the support they need to isolate or quarantine."    The Boston Globe reports there are no more state-funded workers to help track new infections, so local health departments have been advised by the state to only do contact tracing for COVID-19 cases in group settings where infections are more likely to spread rapidly. That includes health care facilities, homeless shelters, nursing homes, daycare centers and schools. However, MassNotify, a smartphone tool that can notify you "if another user you’ve been near tests positive for COVID-19 within a 14-day period." Because the tool allows for limited contact tracing and not all identified cases, this policy is coded as a 1.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050255/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-community-tracing-collaborative-ctc  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050524/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/enable-massnotify-on-your-smartphone

column43: Fully vaccinated individuals should get tested if they:  -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.  -Have had close contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. You should get tested within 3-5 days after exposure.  -Are traveling internationally and returning to the United States. Fully vaccinated international travelers are required to get tested three days before travel by air into the U.S. and should also get tested 3-5 days after their trip.    Unvaccinated individuals should get tested if they:   -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.   -Have come in contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. If they do not have symptoms, they should wait at least six days after their last known exposure to COVID-19 before they get tested.  -Take part in activities that put them at higher risk for COVID-19 because they cannot physically distance as needed to avoid exposure, such as travel, attending large social or mass gatherings, or being in crowded or poorly ventilated indoor settings.    If available through an employer or another organization, unvaccinated individuals can be part of a program where they get tested regularly for COVID-19.    See Archive:  https://archive.vn/fUjTw

column9: Latest bulletin:   As we begin the new year, school leaders are requesting updated COVID-19 guidance, particularly to changes that have occurred to the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) close contact and quarantine practices.    At this time, schools should follow the most recent PA Department of Health (DOH) Health Alert (PA-HAN) on Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population that was released last Thursday. (615 - 12/30/2021 - UPD - UPDATE: Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population (PDF))    As with previous updates in guidance, schools are expected to follow the new community guidelines. The CDC has indicated that there will be additional guidance for more specific settings, including schools, released in the near future. DOH will review and update the community guidance in the PA-HAN accordingly if and when CDC makes any further adjustments. Please note that this is a very fluid situation. We appreciate your patience as we work through these changes together.    https://archive.vn/pEyJ8    Two southeastern Pennsylvania school districts announces school closures due to the coronavirus on the heels of their winter breaks.  The Upper Darby and Lower Merion school districts closed schools Monday as case counts rise.  In Lower Merion: If district schools have adequate staffing, in-person learning will resume Tuesday.  Students will also have the option to learn virtually through Jan. 14.  https://archive.vn/UWo4W
column43: The Wolf Administration today announced the launch of a new, free COVID-19 testing site in Delaware County and highlighted the efforts taking place to support Pennsylvanians and community partners on COVID-19 testing.    “To be clear, the best way for Pennsylvanians to protect themselves and vulnerable populations and prevent hospitalization from COVID-19 is for eligible individuals to get vaccinated and boosted,” said Gov. Tom Wolf. “We know that COVID-19 tests are also an important tool to help prevent the spread of this contagious disease, especially as we enter cold and flu season and symptoms for cold, flu and COVID-19 may seem similar. My administration is collaborating with health systems, communities, school districts and the private sector to support their current needs and incentivize the public to get tested before engaging with the public.”     https://archive.vn/Tsvsr
column55: Today, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration amended the emergency use authorization (EUA) for the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine to:  Expand the use of a single booster dose to include use in individuals 12 through 15 years of age.  Shorten the time between the completion of primary vaccination of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine and a booster dose to at least five months.  Allow for a third primary series dose for certain immunocompromised children 5 through 11 years of age. column9: Schools must verify student and staff vaccinations. "Fully vaccinated students and staff who do not have symptoms do not have to quarantine when exposed to COVID-19 and may not require COVID-19 testing as indicated below. Further, while universal masking is required of all students and staff now, there is the possibility in the future that fully vaccinated people may no longer be required to wear masks indoors."    Correct use of cloth face coverings or masks helps prevent the spread of COVID-19 and is required when indoors at K-12 facilities for all school personnel, students, and visitors. There are specific exceptions based on age, development, or disability.    The CDC’s order requiring masks on public transportation, regardless of vaccination status, applies to school buses and transportation. Passengers and drivers are required to wear a mask on school buses.     All school personnel, volunteers, visitors, and students must wear cloth face coverings, or an acceptable alternative (e.g., surgical mask or clear face shield with a drape), at school when indoors in accordance with the Secretary of Health’s Mask Order.    Schools should maintain physical distance of three feet or more between students in classroom settings to the degree possible and reasonable, that allows for full-time, in-person learning for all students.     This guidance has been updated on december 17, 2021; In response to recent sports-related outbreaks, the testing requirements for high-risk  sporting activities has been updated to require screening testing of all athletes, coaches, trainers and supporting personnel, regardless of vaccination status.    For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/RXAD4
column27: Citizens are encouraged to delay their travel plans due to the pandemic. If they must travel, it is recommended that they are fully vaccinated, wear masks, social distance, get tested before traveling, and self monitor for COVID-19 related symptoms. However, utilities will continue to waive deposits for new customers and all late fees through March 29, 2022, according to a Utilities and Transportation Commission order. column41: The Washington Department of Health has built a website dedicated to inform the public on vaccination and other COVID-19 resources.     For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/m98zA
column43: No change. Testing is available to all, although it is recommended that one "seek testing if you have symptoms of COVID-19 or have been in close contact with someone who may be positive for COVID-19. You should get tested immediately if having symptoms, or 3-5 days after suspected exposure, even if you don’t experience any symptoms."  There are no out of pocket cost for tests performed at county or state-supported test sites. Many tests, particularly for people experiencing symptoms, can be billed to insurance or subsidized by the Department of Health.    For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/XmyTv
column45: No change. Contact tracing starts with a person who tested positive for COVID-19. This person will be advised to stay home except to get medical care until they are no longer contagious. A trained interviewer will reach out to the person who has tested positive and ask for the contact information of close contacts (A close contact is a person who has been within 6 feet, for 15 minutes or more, of someone who tested positive for COVID-19). Next, the interviewer will reach out to the contacts to let them know they have been exposed. Contacts stay home to watch for symptoms for 14 days after they were exposed.     For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/0kiER
column52: No changes. Because of a steep increase in disease transmission in Washington, the Secretary of Health is requiring that everyone five years of age and older wear a mask in public indoor settings and at large, outdoor events with 500 or more attendees. There are some exceptions to the mask requirement, including:  > Children under five years of age. However, children age two to four years old can wear a mask under close adult supervision.   > People with a medical or mental health condition or disability that prevents them from wearing a mask.   > Anyone who is working alone, regardless of vaccination status.  > Verified fully vaccinated workers who are working in an area not accessible to the public.   > Athletes who play indoor sports and who are actively engaged in competition or practice (masks are still required on sidelines and in team meetings).   > Small indoor private gatherings and outdoor events with fewer than 500 people, where physical distancing is possible.     For more information, please see:   https://archive.ph/Rv2ee
column55: Vaccines are available for those 5 years old or older. There are no costs to the individual who is getting vaccinated. It is also not necessary to be a U.S citizen to get vaccinated.     For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/9OX5D
column58: No changes. Governor Jay Inslee issued Proclamation 20-46.3 (pdf) April 8, 2021, amending Proclamation 20-05 (pdf), which prevents all employers, public or private, from failing to provide accommodation to high-risk employees, as defined by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), that protects them from risk of exposure to the COVID-19 disease on the job. This ensures that elderly workers can be protected.     Regarding indoor visitation in nursing homes and long term care facilities the safest practice is for patients and visitors to wear source control and physically distance, particularly if either of them are at risk for severe disease or are unvaccinated. If the patient and all their visitor(s) are fully vaccinated, they can choose not to wear source control and to have physical contact. Visitors should wear source control when around other residents or HCP, regardless of vaccination status.    For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/c5qVl
